node.text:
As one of the first Meteorology graduates at the College of Charleston, Mikel Hannah-Harding is living his dream as a weatherman for @wrdw_wagt! 

He decided to go to the #CollegeofCharleston because it had a physics major with a concentration in meteorology. As fortune would have it, in 2017, the College became the only undergraduate institution in South Carolina with a bachelor’s degree in #meteorology, right in time for Hannah-Harding to be one of the first to graduate with the major.

Read more about @slimfinesse15 at today.cofc.edu 

#cofc #southcarolina #charlestonsc @cofc.ssm

node.text:
Systems Engineering major Carter Blanton is getting his fair share this summer working at touchscreen and monitor company @goldfingermonitors. He's had the opportunity to produce CAD drawings, test logic boxes and build motherboards. 🖥️ 

Why Study #Engineering at CofC?
"I applied to a lot of colleges...but those engineering programs are so big, I didn’t feel that I could truly make my mark and be noticed as well as I could here. And as soon as I walked through the Cistern Yard, I just knew right then and there that this was it. It’s just so beautiful. Also hearing about the program from Dr. Narayanan Kuthirummal, his explanation about systems engineering really drew me into the College’s program, too. A systems engineer puts all of the parts together, and I like to think big"

🔗 Read more at link in bio. And follow @cofc.ssm for more!

#collegeofcharleston #cofc #systemsengineering #charlestonsc #engineeringstudent #summerinternship #CofCNext

College of Charleston MS in Environmental and Sustainability Studies program candidate, Amanda Namsinh is spending her summer supporting the South Carolina Sea Grant Consortium! Amanda’s internship with the Consortium focuses on volunteer coordination efforts for a local salt marsh restoration and community science project in Charleston. Working with the South Carolina Department of Natural Resources, Amanda and fellow #CofC volunteers, classmate Kayli Paterson and alum Rebecca Fanning, spend their days planting Spartina grass to rebuild salt marsh areas.
